 Its reasons are as follows: 1) Relevant preferences and dislikes extracted from my self‑introduction:
- Preferences: harmony‑first, inventive multitrack arrangements (Brian Wilson–style); mono/analog tape warmth; preserved transient punch and micro‑dynamics through tasteful remastering; tight sequencing that rewards front‑to‑back listening; guitar‑forward mixes, punchy transient mixes and groove‑first rhythmic momentum; concise, melody‑first pop/rock singles and reliable packaging/metadata.  
- Dislikes: intimate close‑mic, live‑room or minimally polished acoustic presentations; blended/mellow harmonies that dilute distinct vocal personalities; overly lush orchestral/synth‑dense productions or excessive multi‑part stacking that blunts rhythmic attack; under‑mastered releases; spectacle‑driven live recordings; ambiguous titling or scant liner notes.
2) Evaluation of the two candidates against those points:
- CD 1 (late‑’70s AOR, Boston vein) ticks several core boxes: it’s tightly sequenced, offers layered multi‑tracked harmonized guitars (harmony and multitrack focus), has warm analog sheen and punchy‑yet‑roomy tones (analog warmth + preserved headroom/dynamics), is guitar‑forward in a big, punchy way, and explicitly “avoids front‑of‑mix close‑mic vocals and over‑orchestration.” The polished remaster that preserves headroom and dynamics directly matches my preference for remastering that keeps transient punch and micro‑dynamics. The AOR guitar harmonies and punchy transient character align with my taste for groove and rhythmic momentum rather than ambient or overly intimate presentations.
- CD 2 (pristinely mastered, studio‑focused singles) also has strong technical merits: warm analogue timbre, preserved transients, tight sequencing and detailed liner notes — all positives. Where it diverges from my priorities is the emphasis on “theatrical lead vocals [that] command yet retain space and narrative intimacy.” My dislike of intimate close‑mic or lead‑dominated presentations (and my preference for harmony‑first, distinctive vocal personalities rather than a single theatrical lead) makes that vocal emphasis less desirable. CD 2’s strengths in clarity and narrative intimacy are attractive but skew toward a lead‑centric listening experience rather than the multitrack harmony/guitar‑forward sound I prize.
3) Why I chose CD 1 and rejected CD 2 (specifics):
- Choice justification (CD 1): The CD’s layered, multi‑tracked harmonized guitars and warm analog sheen are the closest match to my core preference for harmony‑first, inventive multitrack arrangements and analog warmth. Its avoidance of front‑of‑mix close‑mic vocals directly addresses my dislike of intimate, lead‑dominated close‑mic presentation. The preservation of headroom and dynamics in the remastering means transient punch and micro‑dynamics — which I prize for rhythmic impact and distinct vocal/instrumental textures — are likely intact. The Boston/AOR guitar energy, punchy‑yet‑roomy tones and tight sequencing fit my taste for guitar‑forward mixes and groove‑first momentum better than a theatrical singer‑led record would. Overall, CD 1 preserves the multitrack harmony/guitar attack and remastering philosophy I want, without the over‑orchestration or lead‑dominance I avoid.
- Rejection rationale (CD 2): While CD 2 meets technical desires (pristine mastering, warm analogue timbre, preserved transients, tight sequencing and good liner notes), its emphasis on a commanding, theatrical lead vocal works against my preference for harmony‑first multitrack interplay and risks a more lead‑centric, intimate narrative delivery. That vocal framing could dilute the multi‑part harmonic interplay and guitar‑forward rhythmic attack I prize. In short, CD 2 is sonically excellent but oriented toward a different listening priority (lead‑narrative clarity and vocal intimacy) than my preference for harmony‑driven, punchy, guitar‑forward, analog‑warm productions. For my stated tastes, the late‑’70s AOR disc is the better match.

