- CD 1 (Warmly remastered single edits/radio mixes…): explicitly preserves dynamics and headroom, uses transient‑preserving mastering (keeps instruments slightly ahead of vocals for immediacy and punch), offers lush, tight multi‑tracked harmonies, controlled low end and clear instrument separation, cohesive sequencing and informative liner notes. Those points hit multiple core preferences: inventive multi‑track harmonies, preserved analogue transient snap and punch, clear instrument separation (so harmonies and lead can coexist without masking), and sequencing + liner notes — all directly stated. The transient‑preserving mastering and controlled low end address my dislike of over‑polished, flattened mixes by keeping punch and micro‑dynamics intact.
- CD 2 (1962–1966 single anthology…): strongly aligns with my taste for concise 2–3‑minute original mixes, warm analogue sonics, minimal overdubs and tight three‑part harmonies that support the lead — excellent for intimate, vocal‑first, melody‑driven listening. The close‑miked, midrange‑forward jangly guitars and tactile room immediacy are attractive when I want intimate, nearfield mixes. However, CD 2 emphasizes minimal overdubs and a plain three‑part approach rather than lush, inventive multi‑tracking or bold, dramatic arrangements. It also doesn’t call out cohesive sequencing or informative liner notes, and its “weathered, close‑miked leads” and jangly midrange presentation suggest a more intimate, inward sound rather than the arena‑scale, punchy guitar presence and dramatic multi‑tracked harmonies I prize.
3) Why I choose CD 1 and reject CD 2
- I chose CD 1 because it best satisfies the combination of priorities that define my highest preferences: theatrical, personality‑driven lead vocals paired with inventive multi‑tracked harmonies and bold-sounding single edits that retain analogue warmth and transient snap. CD 1 explicitly promises lush, tight multi‑tracked harmonies (matching my Brian Wilson–style multitrack preference), transient‑preserving mastering and controlled low end (addressing my need for punchy guitar tone and preserved micro‑dynamics), and cohesive sequencing plus informative liner notes (which I value highly for front‑to‑back listening and metadata). Importantly, the mastering and separation are described in ways that avoid the over‑polished, roomy AOR sound I dislike.
- I reject CD 2 not because it’s bad — it very much fits my taste when I want intimate, compact 2–3‑minute singles and vocal‑first mixes — but because it leans toward a weathered, close‑miked, minimal‑overdub presentation rather than the more dramatic, multi‑tracked, harmony‑rich, punchy single‑edits I crave as my primary preference. CD 2’s strengths (intimacy, minimal overdubs, midrange jangly guitars) are somewhat at odds with my desire for arena‑scale energy, inventive multitrack arrangements and explicit sequencing/liner‑note support; therefore CD 1 is the better overall match to the full set of preferences and the specific dislikes I try to avoid.

