- The tactile, close‑mic George Michael compilation checks virtually every box: close‑mic, lyric‑forward vocals with revealed breath and intimate phrasing match my desire for natural vocal micro‑detail and a centered, front‑and‑center lead. Its “transparent, dynamics‑preserving mastering” and “generous headroom” directly address my dislike of over‑compression and excessive loudness. The description of “lean tape warmth adds presence without softening attack” aligns with my taste for tasteful analogue warmth that preserves transient snap. “Tight low end, transient‑forward guitars, punchy drums” matches my preference for well‑defined rhythm section and punchy transients. Finally, “tasteful overdubs” and “concise, remix‑friendly greatest‑hits sequencing” suit my preference for layered harmonies that don’t bury the lead and for concise, radio‑ready sequencing.
- Greatest Hits, Vol. 1 is also strong in important ways—low compression, tape warmth, preserved transients and headroom, presence‑forward breathing lead vocals centered, lush harmonies, and transparent mastering with subtle limiting. Those features are broadly compatible with my tastes. However, two details make it the less ideal fit for me: the emphasis on “wide, natural imaging” and “lush harmonies” suggests a more spacious, era‑faithful presentation that may introduce more ambient width or chorus layering than I prefer for a strictly dry, centered lead. Also, the mention of “subtle limiting” (while mild) indicates some degree of peak control that is not as explicitly dynamics‑preserving as the first compilation’s description. In short, Vol. 1 leans more into lush, wide, era‑faithful presentation—excellent—yet it risks adding the extra spatial/tonal coloration and non‑centered imaging I try to avoid.
