The user updates his self-description as follows: I now favor polished, mid‑forward pop/rock with anthemic, arena‑ready impact — pronounced production sheen, gated/punchy drums, dense midband and a produced low end that propels hooks; multitracked, theatrical lead vocals and stacked harmonies that sit proudly in the mix. 
I still enjoy concise, radio‑ready 2–3 minute songs, tight, hooky arrangements, crystalline layered harmonies, tactile bass–drum lock and a touch of analogue warmth that preserves vocal micro‑detail and replayable snap. Modest compression that keeps groove integrity and clear separation remains valuable. 
Dislikes: raw, downtuned, riff‑centric mixes built on raspy, in‑the‑room vocals with dominant tube overdrive, extended solos and airy room ambience that undermine immediacy; underproduced, overly tape‑warm masters that feel loose and murky; harsh/overbright highs or mixes that bury the melodic lead or kill the pop immediacy I prefer.

The positive CD has the following updated information: Polished, mid‑forward Queen Greatest Hits — appeals to listeners who prefer anthemic, radio‑ready 2–3 minute songs. Dense midband, multitracked theatrical lead vocals and stacked harmonies sit proudly; tight hooks, tactile bass–drum lock and polished low end keep vocal immediacy without brick‑wall compression.

